      "content": "Sure, let's break it down further. According to Bernoulli's principle, when the speed of a fluid (in this case, air) increases, its pressure decreases. So, when air flows over the top surface of an airfoil, it has to travel a longer distance in the same amount of time compared to the air flowing underneath the wing. This causes the air on top to speed up, and as a result, its pressure decreases. Meanwhile, the air flowing underneath the wing moves slower, and its pressure remains higher. This pressure difference between the top and bottom surfaces of the wing creates an upward force, known as lift.\n\nNow, let's talk about the angle of attack. The angle of attack is the angle between the wing's chord line (an imaginary straight line from the leading edge to the trailing edge of the wing) and the oncoming airflow. When the angle of attack increases, the airflow over the top surface of the wing becomes more turbulent, which can further increase the speed of the air and decrease its pressure. However, if the angle of attack becomes too large, the airflow can separate from the wing's surface, causing a sudden loss of lift and potentially leading to a stall. So, the angle of attack plays a",
